This post is part of a series of corollaries to the Inglorious Web series. It stands alone, but the examples make more sense if you've read the architecture post first.

There's a decision every frontend developer makes early in a project, usually without realizing it's a decision: where does state live?

It feels like a technical question. It's actually an architectural one. Most frameworks default to local state and make global state expensive. Inglorious Web flips the default: state is global unless you intentionally isolate it.

The difference looks like this:

Every mainstream approach has a point where the model strains. The strain always comes from the same place — state that was supposed to stay contained, didn't. Here are three projects, three frameworks, and three different versions of why that matters.



 Fattutto: Context API Hits Its Limits

In 2018 I was hired as lead front-end architect on Fattutto, an invoicing application. We were a small team — two front-enders, two back-enders — working intensively for two months. Redux existed but RTK didn't, and plain Redux felt too verbose for what we thought would be a modest amount of global state. Context API was a reasonable choice.

And it was fine — for a while. The problem with Context API isn't that it's wrong for global state. The problem is performance: every consumer re-renders whenever that context's value changes, unless you split your contexts as finely as possible. As features accumulated, each new concern that needed to be shared got its own provider. By the time the app was mature, the root looked like this:

<ThemeContext.Provider value={...}>
 <UserContext.Provider value={...}>
 <LicenceContext.Provider value={...}>
 <IdsToRemoveContext.Provider value={...}>
 <SelectionContext.Provider value={...}>
 <PageViewsContext.Provider value={...}>
 <PreferencesContext.Provider value={...}>
 <SidebarsContext.Provider value={...}>
 <Enhanced {...props} />
 </SidebarsContext.Provider>
 </PreferencesContext.Provider>
 </PageViewsContext.Provider>
 </SelectionContext.Provider>
 </IdsToRemoveContext.Provider>
 </LicenceContext.Provider>
 </UserContext.Provider>
</ThemeContext.Provider>

 Enter fullscreen mode


 Exit fullscreen mode


Eight nested providers. The team that took over after me eventually reduced that number — proving Context is malleable enough to refactor, and that it wasn't a bad choice in the first place. But the growth happened, and reversing it required deliberate effort. That's the limit of the model.



 Tetra Pak: The Right Tool, Right from the Start

In 2020 I was hired as lead front-end architect at Tetra Pak for an industrial HMI — a four-year project building the interface for factory control systems. I'd internalized the Fattutto lesson: even if the initial state seemed small, I went full RTK from day zero. That looked like overkill at first. By the end of the project, the store had grown to this:

export default configureStore({
 reducer: {
 auth, config, dashboard, drawer, changePwdModal, deleteModal,
 alarms, alarmsHistory, kits, lineStatus, maneuverItems, recipes,
 // ... 30+ slices in total
 },
})

 Enter fullscreen mode


 Exit fullscreen mode


Not overkill. The architecture was right, and I'm proud of it. The problem was ergonomic: creating a new RTK slice required enough ceremony that junior developers consistently reached for useState instead. In React with RTK, that's sometimes the correct call — creating a slice for a dropdown's open/closed state is genuine overhead, and useState is the right tool for truly isolated UI state. The problem is that "truly isolated" is a bet, and the bet doesn't always pay off.

The concrete example: a list of maneuver items, each rendered as an accordion. The user clicks a header to expand it, edits settings in the form inside, and clicks save. Saving should trigger multiple effects across different parts of the app: the accordion collapses, a recipe bar appears asking "do you want to save this change to the recipe too?", and potentially other reactions elsewhere.

With local state, the first instinct looks like this:

function ManeuverItem({ item }) {
 const [isOpen, setIsOpen] = useState(false)

 return (
 <div>
 <button onClick={() => setIsOpen(!isOpen)}>{item.name}</button>
 {isOpen && (
 <ManeuverForm
 item={item}
 onSubmit={(saved) => {
 saveItem(saved)
 setIsOpen(false)
 // but how do we tell the recipe bar to appear?
 // and collapse all other items?
 // and trigger anything else that cares?
 }}
 />
 )}
 </div>
 )
}

 Enter fullscreen mode


 Exit fullscreen mode


The comment is the problem. onSubmit doesn't know about the recipe bar. It can't reach the other accordion items. Every effect that needs to happen requires either prop drilling, a callback passed from above, or a new RTK slice. The state that felt local at definition time turned out to be needed in five other places.

A state manager that's too painful to use correctly is almost as bad as no state manager at all.



 Heineken: Multiple Sources of Truth

More recently I was brought in on an Angular project for Heineken. This isn't an Angular problem specifically — almost every framework implicitly accepts multiple sources of truth as a normal condition. Forms manage their own state. Routing state lives in the URL. Filters live in a service. Default configuration lives somewhere else. The ecosystem treats this as pragmatic.

Until it isn't. In one case, navigating to a URL was supposed to apply a default workcenter to the query string. Other parameters were added on top. But something kept removing the workcenter — a race between the URL history, the filter state, the default configuration, each one writing to the query string independently, each one unaware of the others. Days of debugging, because there was no single place to ask "what is the current routing state?"

This isn't unusual. It's the norm. And it's worth naming, because it means the single source of truth principle isn't just a Redux dogma — it's the thing that makes routing state debuggable.

Three different stacks, three different teams, the same failure mode: state escaping the place it was supposed to live.



 Inglorious Web: Global by Default, Free of Charge

All three stories share a root cause: state that someone decided was local, wasn't. The fix in each case required effort — refactoring contexts, adding slices, untangling sources of truth — because the architecture didn't make global state cheap enough to reach for from the start.

Before addressing the obvious objection ("you don't need a global store, you need signals"), let me show what the Inglorious Web version looks like. Then I'll come back to it.

Here's the maneuver accordion:

const maneuverItem = {
 create(entity) {
 entity.isOpen = false
 },

 toggle(entity, _, api) {
 if (!entity.isOpen) {
 api.notify('maneuverItem:collapse') // enqueued first — collapses all
 api.notify(`#${entity.id}:open`) // enqueued second — opens this one
 } else {
 entity.isOpen = false
 }
 },

 open(entity) {
 entity.isOpen = true
 },

 collapse(entity) {
 entity.isOpen = false
 },

 save(entity, payload, api) {
 saveItem(payload)
 entity.isOpen = false
 api.notify('maneuverItemSave', payload) // broadcast — anyone who cares reacts
 },

 render(entity, api) {
 return html`
 <div class="maneuver-item">
 <button @click=${() => api.notify(`#${entity.id}:toggle`)}>
 ${entity.name}
 </button>
 ${entity.isOpen ? html`
 <maneuver-form
 .item=${entity}
 @submit=${(e) => api.notify(`#${entity.id}:save`, e.detail)}
 ></maneuver-form>
 ` : ''}
 </div>
 `
 },
}

 Enter fullscreen mode


 Exit fullscreen mode


The event queue is what makes toggle work correctly. api.notify() enqueues events rather than firing them immediately — so maneuverItem:collapse hits all entities first, then #maneuver1:open fires, leaving exactly one item open. The order is deterministic and explicit.

And elsewhere in the app, the recipe bar simply listens:

const recipeBar = {
 maneuverItemSave(entity, payload) {
 entity.pendingChange = payload
 entity.isVisible = true
 },
}

 Enter fullscreen mode


 Exit fullscreen mode


No callbacks. No prop drilling. No knowledge of the component tree. maneuverItemSave is a broadcast — every entity with that handler reacts independently. Adding a new reaction means adding a handler to a new type, nothing else.

This looks like classes with methods. It isn't. The type object holds no state — create() fires when the entity is added to the store and initializes its state there. toggle(), open(), collapse(), save() are reducers. Everything lives in the store, accessible to any other entity, debuggable, and testable by calling a function.

Multiple instances are declared explicitly or created at runtime:

// Static
const entities = {
 maneuver1: { type: 'maneuverItem', name: 'Approach' },
 maneuver2: { type: 'maneuverItem', name: 'Lift' },
 maneuver3: { type: 'maneuverItem', name: 'Deposit' },
}

// Or dynamically as data arrives
maneuverItems.forEach((mi) =>
 store.notify('add', { id: mi.id, type: 'maneuverItem', name: mi.name })
)

 Enter fullscreen mode


 Exit fullscreen mode


Each instance gets its own independent state in the store. Adding a new maneuver item type means writing another type object — same shape, same cost, no additional infrastructure.

The router follows the same principle — web history and store state kept in sync as a single entity, with every navigation visible as an event in Redux DevTools:

const { route, path, params } = api.getEntity('router')

api.notify('#router:navigate', '/workcenter/42?filter=active')

 Enter fullscreen mode


 Exit fullscreen mode


The Heineken race condition — multiple services writing to the query string independently — would have been visible immediately. One entity, one source of truth, every change traceable.

When state changes, Inglorious Web re-renders the whole tree and lets lit-html handle the DOM diff surgically. No useEffect firing unexpectedly, no stale closures. The form saves, the event broadcasts, the store updates, the tree re-renders, the accordion closes, the recipe bar appears. Every step is explicit and traceable. The benchmarks post has the full numbers — the short version is 120 FPS on dashboards without any optimization work.



 "But You Don't Need a Store — You Need Signals"

The objection is fair, and it's worth addressing directly: signals solve re-render granularity without a store. A signal for isOpen on each accordion item would work. Fine-grained reactivity would update only the affected DOM node.

The problem isn't the re-renders — as the benchmarks show, full-tree rendering with lit-html is fast enough that the difference is imperceptible in practice. The problem is the dependency graph. Signals are implicit: the runtime tracks which signals were read during rendering, and re-runs when they change. That graph is invisible, lives in the framework's memory, and doesn't show up in your DevTools. When something updates unexpectedly — or fails to update — you're debugging a system you can't inspect.

The event model is explicit: every state transition is a named event you can grep, every handler is a function you can call in a test, every change is visible in Redux DevTools. That's the tradeoff. For the full argument, it's in the first post of the series.



 The Decision You're Actually Making

When you reach for useState, you're making a bet: that this state will never need to be shared. In React, that bet sometimes pays off — a dropdown that genuinely never coordinates with anything else is a fine use of local state, and creating a Redux slice for it is real overhead. The friction isn't imaginary.

But the asymmetry is brutal in one direction: keeping state local when it should be global is cheap to write and expensive to undo. The Fattutto pyramid, the Tetra Pak accordion, the Heineken routing race — all of them started as decisions that felt small.

In Inglorious Web the asymmetry disappears. Global state looks like local state — a create() handler reads almost like a useState initializer, a type object reads almost like a component. The difference is that everything ends up in the store, accessible to everything else, at no extra cost. You're not choosing between local convenience and global power. You just write the type, and the store takes care of the rest.

The decision still exists. But now the safe choice is also the easy one.

